No, I don't think they did really. They - they'd try and - well on the farm to put you through - you go out and - do things and - told what - how things should be so and how it
 should be - got ready, the ground and - how - what length of time they should be - treated and all that and - you would go to market and see what things are selling, keep you in touch with the things but he didn't go in for - not to be a - a business man
,
 more or less - there's lots of things on a farm you've got to learn and got to - go by, and the seasons and the comings and goings. Crops got got to be sewed at the right time and - I remember an old farmer who was talking to my father and - he said to h
i
m - finished heeling corn yet? And he said, oh no, he said - got one more field to do. Well he said, it's near the end of April, he - he said, they always had corn in fall, he says, April month yet, you know, April month yet, he said. Well you see he was 
g
one on the practically last day in April you see. Well - see that - father was there more or less the - they go on the seasons you see, get the corn in the right season because - it makes a difference you see for the length of straw and all that, and whet
her it'll stand up to the weather, all these things, and whether it's - rolled and packed properly and all these things, conditions they put in crops - would - and you had to learn it you see.
